With the var keyword the variable will be the exact same type as what you initialize it to, not an interface.<p><pre><code>  List<Foo> list = new ArrayList<Foo>();
</code></pre>
...is programming towards an interface, whereas<p><pre><code>  var list = new ArrayList<Foo>();
</code></pre>
...isn't, because the type of list will be ArrayList. I think his point was that with the new Java stuff you could instead do<p><pre><code>  List<Foo> list = new ArrayList<>();
</code></pre>
...which would then be explicitly programming towards an interface, while still not having to type so bleeding much.
